'''David-William Gibson''' is an American journalist, author, radio host, and cultural critic. He shared a 2016 [[National Magazine Award]] for his work on “This Is the Story of One Block in Bed-Stuy, Brooklyn” for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 National Magazine Awards|url=http://www.magazine.org/asme/2016-national-magazine-awards|website=American Society of Magazine Editors|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>
Gibson has published two oral histories: ''Not Working: People Talk About Losing a Job and Finding Their Way in Today’s Changing Economy'' and ''The Edge Becomes the Center: An Oral History of Gentrification in the 21st Century'',<ref>{{cite web|title=DW Gibson|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/230958/dw-gibson|website=Penguin Random House|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> which won the inaugural Brooklyn Eagle Literary Prize awarded by the [[Brooklyn Public Library]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sutton|first1=Benjamin|title=A Complex Portrait of Gentrification in New Yorkers’ Own Words|url=https://hyperallergic.com/256081/a-complex-portrait-of-gentrification-in-new-yorkers-own-words/|website=Hyperallergic|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn Public Library Announces Eagles Literary Prize Winners|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/newsbrief/index.html?record=479|website=Publishers Weekly|accessdate=22 March 2018|date=26 October 2015}}</ref> and a 2016 [[Independent Publisher Book Awards]] Gold Medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Independent Publisher Book Awards Regional & Ebook Results|url=http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=2046|website=Independent Publisher|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> He has written for ''[[Harper's Magazine|Harper’s]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The Nation]]'', and ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=DW Gibson|url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/people/dw-gibson/|website=WNYC Studios|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> He has contributed on-air to [[NPR]]’s ''[[All Things Considered]]''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gibson|first1=DW|title=Wicked And Delicious: Devouring Roald Dahl|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/08/13/158415389/wicked-and-delicious-devouring-roald-dahl|website=NPR|publisher=All Things Considered|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=August 13, 2012}}</ref> and ''Midday on [[WNYC]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Neil Gaiman Explores the World of Norse Mythology|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/inside-world-norse-mythology/|website=WNYC|publisher=Midday on WNYC|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=Mar 6, 2018}}</ref>
